engineeringDiary.laser.title=Laser
engineeringDiary.laser.howToMakeProgress=???
engineeringDiary.laser.page0=Who doesn't like lasers?
engineeringDiary.laser.page1=Its never been a secret to anyone that the Diamond is the purest of Gems. It was you however that discovered its far more important energy directional capabilities. @ @ Originally, it was an attempt to achieve
engineeringDiary.laser.page2=long distance power transmission. Directing energy beams through Diamonds and Redstone so they could propel it through air instead of passing through Pipes. It was hard work until you figured out the only thing it
engineeringDiary.laser.page3=wouldn’t burn through was Obsidian, and then even longer to realise you were just not capable of converting the new light into the old one. Still this process of
engineeringDiary.laser.page4=Light Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Redstone (LASER for short) holds some interesting properties, and you wonder what the future holds for it.

engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.title=Assembly Table
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.howToMakeProgress=???
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.page0=Precision crafting
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.page1=It started with your attempt of long range energy transmission. Your plan was to pass the laser through the Redstone coated Diamond (which was placed on an Obsidian Tablet) and then place it on a Kinesis Pipe. That just didn’t work.
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.page2=It wasn’t until later that you realised a Gear could perfectly fit on the Pipe hole. Any Gear other than the Diamond one would break from the raw power that’s sent by the laser, so that’s the one you put there.
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.page3=The lasers cut it in seemingly random order, but after watching it for a while you start to notice some patterns. This table clearly holds potential for assembling objects in specific ways. You wonder how it would react
engineeringDiary.assemblyTable.page4=to the placement of different objects on it.

engineeringDiary.integrationTable.title=Integration Table
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.howToMakeProgress=???
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page0=Installing upgrades
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page1=Right after discovering that Gates can’t be made from some Chipsets, you just wonder exactly what can be done with them. After a while you decide to stop thinking about it and switch to actually doing something about it. At first you
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page2=try to combine the Chipsets with the Gates themselves, failing. The Assembly Table simply isn’t made for that. So you decide to make a Table that is made for that. @ @ With a simple change (a Diamond to a Redstone Chipset,
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page3=you make a new table, and it is so much different. This new Table was made for integrating things, and that’s what you do. Each Chipset adds something to the Gates, in the form of triggers and actions.
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page4=But that’s not all this Table has to offer. You can actually combine two facades, and its possible to use a Redstone Chipset to tune them with a Pipe Wire of choice, effectively making you able to control which facade is shown
engineeringDiary.integrationTable.page5=by activating or deactivating the Pipe Wire.

engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.title=Advanced Crafting Table
engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.howToMakeProgress=Make items
engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.page0=Better automated crafting
engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.page1=The old Auto Workbench had its uses, but the fact that it can’t handle unstackable items is really starting to annoy you. You decide to do what you do these days, and make a Laser-compatible machine.
engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.page2=By combining a Crafting Table and Chest with a Redstone Chipset (all encased within Obsidian), you make the Advanced Crafting Table. @ @ It uses Lasers to craft whatever you tell it to craft, and the best of all
engineeringDiary.advancedCraftingTable.page3=is that they not only have internal inventories, but they can also access the inventories of connected Advanced Crafting Tables, allowing for compact crafting chains.

engineeringDiary.pipePlug.title=Pipe Plug
engineeringDiary.pipePlug.howToMakeProgress=???
engineeringDiary.pipePlug.page0=Compacter builds
engineeringDiary.pipePlug.page1=You said there’d be other uses… Here they are. Putting the Support Pipe in the Assembly Table caused them to be sliced into little pieces. Little pieces that perfectly fit pipes and blocks them from connecting
engineeringDiary.pipePlug.page2=to one another (one can say they perfectly ‘plug’ into pipes). @ @ A great way to make more compact systems.

