engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.title=Redstone Engine
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.howToMakeProgress=Craft pistons
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.page0=A small bit of power
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.page1=While working with Pistons on a Redstone contraption, it comes to you that they’re pretty interesting blocks, being capable of such important feats only by receiving a Redstone Signal. @ @ After you finish your project,
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.page2=you try to somehow improve them through Gears, without much success. It takes you sometime to realise that you also need to reinforce the piston head, and so when you finally come up with something that works, it is totally different
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.page3=from what you expected. @ @ This new block doesn’t seem to actually be able to move blocks, but the constant movement of the new head looks like it’ll have some applications in the future. Based on its power source,
engineeringDiary.redstoneEngine.page4=you name it the Redstone Engine and move on.

engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.title=Stirling Engine
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.howToMakeProgress=Make Redstone Engines
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.page0=First machine power
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.page1=If Gears can be upgraded, why couldn’t Engines? That’s what you thought when you tried to make a Stone Engine, but apparently you failed. The Engine just didn’t start when you powered it with a Lever, but you keep trying, thinking it might be
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.page2=because of the weak Redstone signal and instead you make some more levers. @ @ By chance, a stick falls into the Engine and it suddenly starts, its power much stronger than the Redstone Engine. Just as quickly
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.page3=as it started, it ends, and you throw more Wood in it. Blocks, this time. @ @ After some experimentation you realise it lasts the same time on the engine as it would on a furnace, and sure enough a piece of Coal also works on the machine.
engineeringDiary.stilringEngine.page4=Too bad it seems to overheat after some time, requiring a long cooldown period. @ @ By the quick movement of the Engine head, you decide to call it the Stirling Engine.

engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.title=Combustion Engine
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.howToMakeProgress=Make Stirling Engines
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page0=More powergen
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page1=After the discovery of the Stirling Engine, you’re sure new Engines can be created from different Gears. What you’re not sure of is what kind of requirements these Engines have to activate. @ @ It turns out this one has a taste for Fluids.
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page2=Specifically, that weird black Oil you found a while back. At first it makes some very loud sounds, and if the burning smell is to go by things aren’t going well… @ @ But sure enough the Engine stabilizes and produces way more energy
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page3=than before, this time its cooldown period even longer. @ @ Curious about its liquid properties, you throw in some water, without realising the Engine still had some Oil inside, you start it up and immediately
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page4=see your error. Though perhaps it wasn’t an error, considering the Engine works just like it had before. You decide to put more Oil and Water in it, and not only do they not mix, the cool water completely denies the
engineeringDiary.combustionEngine.page5=heating of the Engine, theoretically letting it run forever.